1ï¸âƒ£ Frequency Count
ğŸ”¹ Problem

Count the frequency of each character in a string.

ğŸ§  Python Code (4 lines)
s="google"
d={}
for c in s: d[c]=d.get(c,0)+1
print(d)

ğŸ–¥ï¸ Output
{'g': 2, 'o': 2, 'l': 1, 'e': 1}

ğŸ“– Explanation

We create an empty dictionary d.

For each character c:

get(c,0) returns current count (or 0 if not present).

We add 1 and store it back.

Final dictionary stores character â†’ frequency.

â±ï¸ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n)

ğŸ¤ Interview Explanation

â€œI use a hash map to count occurrences in one pass, giving linear time complexity.â€

2ï¸âƒ£ Two Sum using Hash Map
ğŸ”¹ Problem

Check if any two numbers in an array sum to a target.

ğŸ§  Python Code (5 lines)
a=[2,7,11,15]; t=9
s=set()
for x in a:
    if t-x in s: print(True); break
    s.add(x)

ğŸ–¥ï¸ Output
True

ğŸ“– Explanation

We keep a set s of numbers already seen.

For each number x:

Check if target - x exists in the set.

If yes â†’ pair found.

This avoids nested loops.

â±ï¸ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n)

ğŸ¤ Interview Explanation

â€œHashing allows me to reduce the time from O(nÂ²) to O(n) by storing visited elements.â€

ğŸ¤ FAANG Interview Round (Professional Answers)

Q1. What is hashing?
A: Hashing stores data in keyâ€“value format to allow constant-time lookup.

Q2. Why is hashing faster than loops?
A: Because it avoids repeated comparisons and enables direct access.

Q3. Where is frequency count used?
A: Anagrams, duplicates, majority element, and substring problems.

Q4. Can Two Sum be solved without hashing?
A: Yes, using sorting and two pointers, but hashing is faster.

